body: "# Semgrep finding import\n\nSemgrep finding id: 874840453\nRule: javascript.lang.security.audit.prototype-pollution.prototype-pollution-loop.prototype-pollution-loop\nProduct: Code\nSeverity: Medium\nStatus: Open\nConfidence: Low\nCategory: security\nIs Pro Rule: False\nSemgrep autotriage result: False positive\nSemgrep file risk tag: Unspecified\nRepository: unbraind/pm-cli\nBranch: refs/heads/main\nCreated at: 2026-07-03 12:04:25.346236\nLast opened at: 2026-07-03 12:04:25.327899\n\nLinks:\n- Code: https://github.com/unbraind/pm-cli/blob/6f511706628f18743a00a1cfe851e8d1f492684e/src/core/config/nested-settings.ts#L488\n- Semgrep: https://semgrep.dev/orgs/unbrained/findings/874840453\n- Repository: https://github.com/unbraind/pm-cli\n\nRule description:\nPossibility of prototype polluting function detected. By adding or modifying attributes of an object prototype, it is possible to create attributes that exist on every object, or replace critical attributes with malicious ones. This can be problematic if the software depends on existence or non-existence of certain attributes, or uses pre-defined attributes of object prototype (such as hasOwnProperty, toString or valueOf). Possible mitigations might be: freezing the object prototype, using an object without prototypes (via Object.create(null) ), blocking modifications of attributes that resolve to object prototype, using Map instead of object.\n\nAutotriage reason:\nThis matched a read-only property access while traversing a dotted path, not a write that would modify an object prototype. The prototype-pollution concern in the rule message applies to attacker-controlled writes like assigning to __proto__/constructor/prototype, and this snippet only reads values, so the match is likely due to the rule's broad loop-and-index pattern.\n\nImported from downloaded CSV:\nSemgrep_Code_Combined_Findings_2026_07_06.csv (local download, not committed)"
